 Vancouver and the Lower Mainland.\n\nOther over-the-air television stations licensed to Bellingham that are available terrestrially in Vancouver but not carried on cable are [[KBCB]] (channel 24), an affiliate of [[Sonlife Broadcasting Network]] on subchannels 24.1, in high definition, and 24.2, in standard definition; and K24IC-D (channel 28.1), a rebroadcaster of [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] station [[KBTC-TV]] [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]].\n\nAmerican network affiliates on Vancouver cable are from [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]], including [[KOMO-TV|KOMO]] ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]), [[KING-TV|KING]] ([[NBC]]), [[KIRO-TV|KIRO]] ([[CBS]]), [[KCTS-TV|KCTS]] ([[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]), [[KSTW]] ([[The CW Television Network|The CW]]), and [[KCPQ]] ([[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]).\n\n==Magazines==\n*''[[Boulevard Magazine]]'', a west coast luxury lifestyle magazine serving the Chinese-speaking communities of Metro Vancouver,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vancouverboulevard.com/about-us/|title=Vancouver Boulevard - About us|last=|first=|date=2012-03-26|website=Boulevard Chinese Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref> published monthly in English and in Chinese.\n* [[Business in Vancouver]] (BIV) is a weekly business news journal\n*''[[HUSH Magazine]]'', a bi-monthly social commentary and lifestyle magazine for 25- to 40-year-olds, distributed to Downtown Vancouver\n*''[http://www.megaphonemagazine.com/megaphone_magazine Megaphone Magazine]'', sharing stories that explore social justice, culture, politics, and independent arts in Vancouver and Victoria.\n*''[[MONTECRISTO Magazine]]'', a lifestyle quarterly for discerning Vancouverites, published four times a year\n*''[[Resource World Magazine]]'', a bi-monthly magazine distributed in 46 countries that reports on the business of mining and green technologies\n*''[[Vancouver Magazine]]'', a lifestyle magazine with some news features, published 10 times a year\n*''[[What's in Magazine]]'', a Chinese lifestyle magazine for new trends in the Asian community, published once a month\n*''[http://westcoastfamilies.com WestCoast Families]'', a family lifestyle magazine, published 6 times a year, plus specialty issues.\n\n==Online media==\n* ''[http://www.ax3battery.com/ AX3 Battery]'', Asian news and events site\n* ''BC Buzz with [[Dave Michael Garg]]'', online TV & magazine outlet focused on the environment\n* ''[http://www.cambiereport.ca Cambie Report]'', local politics podcast\n* ''[https://dailyhive.com/ Daily Hive]'' (formerly Vancity Buzz), local news and lifestyle outlet\n* ''[[HUSH Magazine]]'', an editorial platform for lifestyle, social commentary and entertainment\n* ''[http://LifeVancouver.jp/ LifeVancouver]'', Japanese news and events site\n* ''[https://politicoast.ca PolitiCoast]'', provincial politics podcast\n* [[Taiyangbao.ca]], a Chinese-language news website produced in association with ''The Vancouver Sun'' newspaper\n* TheProvince.com, a news website produced in ''The Province'' newsroom\n* ''[[The Tyee]]'', alternative news site\n* ''[http://vancouverdesi.com Vancouver Desi]'', a South Asian news portal produced in association with ''The Province'' newspaper\n* ''[[The Vancouver Observer]]'', alternative local news site\n* ''[http://www.vancouverweekly.com/ Vancouver Weekly]'', alternative news weekly site\n*VancouverSun.com, a news website produced in ''The Vancouver Sun'' newsroom\n* ''[http://www.viesmag.com/ VIES Magazine]'', independent entertainment magazine in Vancouver, B.C. with focus on music, sports, food and beverage\n* ''[http://www.thewestendjournal.ca/ The West End Journal]'', independent online community website serving Vancouver's West End / Coal Harbour neighbourhoods\n\n==Media ownership==\nVancouver has some of the most concentrated media ownership in all of Canada. ''[[The Vancouver Sun]]'', ''[[The Province]]'', the ''[[National Post]]'', and 12 community newspapers are all owned by Postmedia Network. Partly in response to that concentration, a group of journalists \u2014 many of them ex-''Sun'' employees \u2014 started up an online news publication, ''[[The Tyee]]'', that posts news and opinion pieces on a nearly daily basis.\n\n==Ethnic media==\nAs of the 2000s there were various formats of media catering to ethnic minorities. They included 80 newspapers, 24 magazines, 15 television stations, 15 radio stations, and 10 printed business directories and online publications. Daniel Ahadi and Catherine A. Murray, the authors of \"Urban Mediascapes and Multicultural Flows: Assessing Vancouver\u2019s Communication Infrastructure,\" wrote that publication turnover, or the creation and failure and publications, was very high.<ref>Ahadi, Daniel and Catherine A. Murray ([[Simon Fraser University]]). \"[http://pages.cmns.sfu.ca/daniel-ahadi/files/2010/07/Ahadi_Mediascapes.pdf Urban Mediascapes and Multicultural Flows: Assessing Vancouver\u2019s Communication Infrastructure]\" (  {{dead link|date=July 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}). ''[[Canadian Journal of Communication]]'', Vol 34 (2009) p. 587-611. CITED: p. 596. \"The status of many of these ethnic outlets is manifestly precarious. Churn is high.\"</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hollywood North]]\n\n{{Media by city in Canada}}\n{{British Columbia TV}}\n{{Vancouver}}\n{{Vancouver Radio}}\n\n[[Category:Media in Vancouver| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of media by city in Canada|Vancouver]]\n[[Category:British Columbia-related lists|Media, Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Vancouver-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision:Add relevant link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Media_in_Vancouver"}
{"title_page": "Climate change adaptation in Greenland", "text_new": "[[File:Flag of Greenland.png|thumb|Flag of Greenland]]\n'''Climate change is a big oof''' is a pressing issue '''i'''n [[Greenland]]. The term [[climate change]] describes long-term changes to the [[climate]] system. Since the 1950s a stark rise in global temperatures has been observed.<ref name=\":4\">IPCC (2014): Climate Change 2014: Synthesis Ree. Pachauri and L.A. Meyer (eds.)]. IPCC, Geneva, Switzerland, 151 pp.</ref> As climate change, whether [[Climate change (general concept)|natural]] or [[Global warming|anthropogenic]], impacts the livelihoods of people across the globe, responses i.e. ways to prepare and adjust under changing vulnerabilities become important. Such responses are commonly discussed under the term adaptation, \"the process of adjustment to actual or expected climate and its effects\",<ref>IPCC, 2014: Annex II: Glossary [Mach, K.J., S. Planton and C. von Stechow (eds.)]. In: Climate Change 2014: Synthesis Report. Contribution of Working Groups I, II and III to the Fifth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change. IPCC, Geneva, Switzerland, pp. 117-130</ref> as defined by the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change|IPCC]].\n\nGeographically [[Greenland]] is situated between the [[Arctic Ocean|Arctic]] and the [[Atlantic Ocean]], with one third of the island being north of the [[Arctic Circle]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Greenland|title=Greenland {{!}} History, Geography, & Culture|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2018-07-12|language=en}}</ref> Since the middle of the 20th century, the [[Arctic]] has been warming at about twice the global rate.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":7\">Lackenbauer, W., Nicol, H. & Greaves, W. (eds.) (2017). One Arctic. The Arctic Council and Circumpolar Governance. Centre for Foreign Policy & Federation.</ref> Rising temperatures put increasing pressure on certain plant and tree species<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nature.org/ourinitiatives/urgentissues/global-warming-climate-change/threats-solutions/|title=The Threats of Climate Change and Global Warming|website=www.nature.org|language=en|access-date=2018-07-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728131557/https://www.nature.org/ourinitiatives/urgentissues/global-warming-climate-change/threats-solutions/|archive-date=2018-07-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> and contribute to Greenland's melting ice sheet.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/05/climate/greenland-ice-melting.html|title=As Greenland Melts, Where's the Water Going?|last=Fountain|first=Henry|access-date=2018-07-12|language=en}}</ref> This affects and changes the livelihood of the Greenlandic population, particularly the [[Inuit]] people, which make up to 80 percent of the total population.<ref name=\":2\" /> Besides the decline of fish stocks, the country's landscape is changing: the melting ice reveals minerals, oil and gas. This has attracted interest from local and foreign investors for potential resource extraction. As new industries are accompanied by new job opportunities and potential wealth, lifestyles are changing. Greenland is in transition, in terms of biophysical as well as cultural and social conditions.\n\n==Changes and developments ==\n===Biophysical===\n[[File:Greenland ice-sheet hg.jpg|alt=|thumb|Greenland Ice Sheet]]\nDue to its geographical location and global climatic patterns such as the [[North Atlantic oscillation|North Atlantic Oscillation]] and volcanic activity,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Box|first=Jason E.|last2=Yang|first2=Lei|last3=Bromwich|first3=David H.|last4=Bai|first4=Le-Sheng|date=2009|title=Greenland Ice Sheet Surface Air Temperature Variability: 1840\u20132007*|journal=Journal of Climate|language=en|volume=22|issue=14|pages=4029\u20134049|doi=10.1175/2009jcli2816.1|issn=0894-8755|citeseerx=10.1.1.175.1565}}</ref> Greenland is exposed to high levels of fluctuations in the natural environment.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Hamilton|first=Lawrence|last2=Lyster|first2=Per|last3=Otterstad|first3=Oddmund|date=2000|title=Social Change, Ecology and Climate in 20th-Century Greenland|journal=Climatic Change|language=en|volume=47|issue=1/2|pages=193\u2013211|doi=10.1023/a:1005607426021|issn=0165-0009}}</ref> The [[Greenland ice sheet]] is the second largest in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.uga.edu/study-2015-melting-greenland-ice-faster-arctic-warming-0616/|title=Study links 2015 melting Greenland ice to faster Arctic warming - UGA Today|date=2016-06-09|work=UGA Today|access-date=2018-07-12|language=en-US}}</ref> Consequently, its melting has a significant impact on a global scale. According to the [[European Environment Agency|European Environmental Agency]] \"the cumulative ice loss from Greenland from 1992 to 2015 was 3 600 Gt (Gigatonnes) and contributed to global [[sea level rise]] by approximately 10 mm.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eea.europa.eu/data-and-maps/indicators/greenland-ice-sheet-3/assessment|title=Greenland and Antarctic ice sheets|work=European Environment Agency|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en}}</ref> The anticipated warming of the oceans and resulting sea level rise<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipcc.ch/report/ar5/syr/|title=Fifth Assessment Report - Synthesis Report|website=www.ipcc.ch|access-date=2018-07-01}}</ref> result in [[coastal erosion]], melting of [[permafrost]] and decreased [[sea ice]] thickness.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ford|first=James D.|last2=Goldhar|first2=Christina|date=2012-09-25|title=Climate change vulnerability and adaptation in resource dependent communities: a case study from West Greenland|url=https://www.int-res.com/abstracts/cr/v54/n2/p181-196/|journal=Climate Research|language=en|volume=54|issue=2|pages=181\u2013196|doi=10.3354/cr01118|issn=0936-577X}}</ref> The areas impacted most in Greenland are those with the highest population density.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Westergaard-Nielsen|first=Andreas|last2=Karami|first2=Mojtaba|last3=Hansen|first3=Birger Ulf|last4=Westermann|first4=Sebastian|last5=Elberling|first5=Bo|date=2018-01-25|title=Contrasting temperature trends across the ice-free part of Greenland|journal=Scientific Reports|language=En|volume=8|issue=1|pages=1586|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-19992-w|issn=2045-2322|pmc=5785469|pmid=29371633}}</ref>\n\n===Socio-economic===\n[[File:Greenland-CIA WFB Map.png|thumb|Map of Greenland]]\nIn July 2017, Greenland's population was 57,713.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/gl.html|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-07-12}}</ref> This number is expected to decline to 54,800 by 2030.<ref name=\":9\" /> Historically, the movement of people and the accompanying change of social conditions is nothing unusual for Greenlanders.<ref name=\":8\" /> Recorded shifts were primarily driven by the search for resources (of e.g. seals and cod). At the beginning of the 21st century, climate change has an unprecedented impact on Greenland.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sellheim|first=Nikolas|date=2016|title=Rethinking Greenland and the Arctic in the era of climate change. New northern horizons. Frank Sejersen. 2015. London & New York: Routledge. xii + 235 p, hardcover. ISBN 978-1-13-884515-2. 90.00\u00a3.|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/polar-record/article/rethinking-greenland-and-the-arctic-in-the-era-of-climate-change-new-northern-horizons-frank-sejersen-2015-london-new-york-routledge-xii-235-p-hardcover-isbn-9781138845152-9000/1037251B5398A51B811651E8DED44F6A|journal=Polar Record|language=en|volume=52|issue=4|pages=500\u2013501|doi=10.1017/S0032247415000893|issn=0032-2474|via=}}</ref> The melting ice sheet enables an easier access to oil, gas and minerals, the exploitation of which creates new economic opportunities.<ref name=\":1\">The Government of Greenland: Greenland's oil and Mineral strategy 2014-2018, available under http://naalakkersuisut.gl/~/media/Nanoq/Files/Publications/Raastof/ENG/Greenland%20oil%20and%20mineral%20strategy%202014-2018_ENG.pdf</ref> This prospect of new jobs, purchasing power, new shipping routes and the possibly resulting entrance into the global market system is linked to the potential of gaining greater independence from [[Denmark]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Putting a damper on previously displayed optimism, the versatility of global commodity markets also poses potential threats.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nBesides potential for tourism development which comes with numerous challenges, in south Greenland the melting ice provides more grazing opportunities for farmers. However, there is also apprehension particularly amongst smaller villages that rely on hunting and fishing (primarily Inuit communities), that climate change will contribute to the end of their traditional lifestyles.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Nuttall|first=Mark|date=2010|title=Anticipation, climate change, and movement in Greenland|url=http://id.erudit.org/iderudit/045402ar|journal=\u00c9tudes/Inuit/Studies|language=en|volume=34|issue=1|pages=21|doi=10.7202/045402ar|issn=0701-1008|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Political===\nAlthough becoming increasingly autonomous, Greenland remains dependent on the [[Denmark|Kingdom of Denmark]] since its colonisation in 1721. In 197], the [[Naalakkersuisut|Home Rule Government]] was established in Greenland. It gained further rights in 2009, which moved Greenland towards self-rule.<ref name=\":2\" /> The government is financially dependent on Denmark which provides 60% of Greenland's annual budget revenue.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Nuttall|first=Mark|date=2008|title=Self Rule in Greenland: Towards the World's First Inuit State?|url=|journal=Indigenous Affairs 3-4/08|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> One of the country's greatest challenges is to ensure modern life styles introduced primarily through the industrialisation processes and triggered by intensive fishery while pursuing economic wealth creation and further independence.<ref name=\":9\">AMAP, 2017. Adaptation Actions for a Changing Arctic (AACA) - Baffin Bay / Davis Strait Region Overview report. Arctic Monitoring and Assessment Programme (AMAP), Oslo, Norway. p. 6</ref> It is for this reason or rather the desire to phase out Denmark's financial support entirely that the Home Rule Government strongly supports and even promotes arising opportunities in the extraction industry.<ref name=\":1\" /> The [[United States Geological Survey]] estimated a total of 141 billion barrels of [[hydrocarbon]]s (approximately 13% of the world's undiscovered oil and 30% of the undiscovered natural gas) to be held beneath Greenlandic surfaces.<ref>'''Gautier, Donald L., 2007:''' ''Assessment of undiscovered oil and gas re- sources of the East Greenland Rift Basins Province'' U.S. Geological Survey Fact Sheet 2007-3077, 4 p.</ref> In 2009, the Greenlandic Government published a lifecycle assessment for the production of aluminium in an [[Alcoa]] smelter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smv.gl/Baggrundsrapporter/lca_2009.pdf|title=Life cycle assessment of aluminium production in a new Alcoa smelter in Greenland|last=Schmidt|first=Jannick H|last2=Thrane|first2=Mikkel|date=2009|access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> The construction of the [[Aluminium smelting|aluminium smelter]] is planned in the town of [[Maniitsoq]].<ref name=\":2\" /> In addition, in 2013 the government decided to lift the ban on the extraction of radioactive minerals such as [[uranium]].<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n== Adaptation approaches ==\n\n=== Perspectives on adaptation ===\nIn order to identify and implement effective measures of adaptation, current developments, such as demographic change and other non-climatic factors of change must be considered simultaneously. A study conducted by the Arctic Monitoring and Assessment Programme (AMAP), a working group of the [[Arctic Council]], distinguishes between short-term and long-term adaptation measures, as well as climate-centered and vulnerability-centered options. In the short-term, adaptation measures can focus on immediate challenges caused by increased extreme weather events, such as heavy rainfalls or melting permafrost (climate-centered). In the long-term, other developments, such as the effects of demographic, social and economic change must be considered when determining how climate change will affect the population (vulnerability-centered).<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Adaptation measures ===\n\n==== The Greenlandic Government ====\nAt the [[2015 United Nations Climate Change Conference]], the then Greenlandic Minister for Finance, Mineral Resources and Foreign Affairs, Vittus Qujaukitsoq described climate change adaptation in Greenland as being a policy priority. He underlined the importance of incorporating the knowledge and experience of the Inuit people to gain an all-encompassing understanding of the ongoing climatic changes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://naalakkersuisut.gl/~/media/Nanoq/Files/Attached%20Files/Engelske-tekster/Taler/Climate%20change%20in%20GreenlandParis.pdf|title=Speech by Minister for Finance, Mineral Resources and Foreign Affairs Mr. Vittus Qujaukitsoq}}</ref>\n\nThe government's website ''[http://climategreenland.gl/en/ Climate Greenland]''<ref>'[http://climategreenland.gl/en/ Climate Greenland]'</ref> is both a resource tool to find relevant organizations or stakeholders, as was well as information on the impacts of climate change on Greenland and how the country is responding to it. It focuses on the four areas 'citizen', 'trade', 'municipality' and 'education'. Climate Change Adaptation is defined as \"being prepared for the challenges caused by the climate changes and about relating to possibilities as well as challenges.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://climategreenland.gl/en/citizen/climate-adaptation/|title=Climate adaptation - Climate Greenland|work=Climate Greenland|access-date=2018-07-04|language=en-US}}</ref> The Government publishes adaptation reports for sectors, such as fisheries, hunting or [[Tourism in Greenland|tourism]].\n\nIn 2009 the Greenland Climate Research Centre was set up in the capital of Greenland, [[Nuuk]]. The centre received a grant of [[Danish krone|DKK]] 35 million by the [[Ministry of Higher Education and Science (Denmark)|Danish Ministry of Science, Technology and Innovation]]. The aim of the centre is to study the impact of climate change on Greenland [[Climate change in the Arctic|and the Arctic]] and the consequences for nature and society. It is linked to the Greenland Institute of Natural Resources and the [[University of Greenland]], Ilisimatusarfik.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.natur.gl/en/communication/news/article/a/new-greenland-climate-research-center/|title=New Greenland Climate Research Center {{!}} Pinngortitaleriffik - Gr\u00f8nlands Naturinstitut|website=www.natur.gl|language=da|access-date=2018-07-04}}</ref>\n\n==== The Arctic Council ====\n[[File:Arctic region CIA.jpg|alt=|thumb|Countries within the Arctic Region]]\nIn 2008, following increased media attention for the Arctic, the five countries adjacent to the [[Arctic Ocean]] (Canada, Denmark (Greenland), Norway, Russia and the United States) published the [[Ilulissat Declaration]]. This proclaims the Arctic states' responsibility to protect the ecosystem of the Arctic Ocean.<ref name=\":7\" /> In addition, the [[Arctic Council|Council's]] Arctic Monitoring and Assessment Programme (AMAP) has published a series of reports one of which looks at adaptation in particular. The 2017 Adaptation Actions for a Changing Arctic (AACA) Report covers the [[Baffin Bay]]/[[Davis Strait]] region which includes the western part of Greenland aiming to offer information \"to assist local decision makers and stakeholders [...] in developing adaptation tools and strategies to better deal with climate change [...].\"<ref name=\":9\" /> Following extensive stakeholder dialogues, the report identified seven themes of local adaptation:\n\n# Living resources\n# Non-living resources (e.g. mineral extraction)\n# Education\n# Human health and well-being\n# Tourism\n# Shipping\n# Infrastructure\n\nThe report concludes that it is crucial to consider the cumulative and cascading effects of change in order to build adaptive capacities. Suggested measures are structural/physical, social as well as institutional. Lastly, as a precursor to adaptation measures, the AACA points out six factors (political leadership, institutional organisation, local and regional leadership, the need for usable science and sufficient funding and public support) to build adaptive readiness.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n== Inuit culture and tradition ==\n=== Traditional ecological knowledge ===\nWidely discussed in academic literature since the 1980s, [[traditional ecological knowledge]] cumulatively consists of knowledge, practices and beliefs about the interaction of living beings and their environment.<ref>Berkes, F. (2008). ''Sacred Ecology.'' New York: Routledge.</ref> In Greenland, traditional knowledge does not only underpin the life of subsistence hunters and fishermen but also more broadly community life and [[Inuit culture|culture]]. While climate change is making practical aspects such as the prediction of weather or animal migration more difficult, it also highlights the importance of traditional knowledge for adaptive capacity building in other areas e.g. the recognition of approaching hazards and survival skills.<ref name=\":9\" /> The process of knowledge transfer between generations for building resilience is also important to address as it is weakened by trends of urbanisation and alternative livelihoods. Such trends can further lead to the alienation of people from their environment. This increases the need for the management of ecosystems which are the base of [[Economy of Greenland|Greenland's]] economic activities, cultural characteristics and natural services.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== The concept of anticipation ===\n[[File:Leaving Kulusuk (33806528314).jpg|thumb|Inuit hunters near Kulusuk, Greenland]]\n[[Greenlandic Inuit]] as a societal group are academically recognised for their \"finely tuned ability to be flexible, to innovate, and to seize opportunities in the environment.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nuttall|first=Mark|date=2010|title=Anticipation, climate change, and movement in Greenland|url=http://www.erudit.org/fr/revues/etudinuit/2010-v34-n1-etudinuit3992/045402ar/|journal=&#201;tudes/Inuit/Studies|language=en|volume=34|issue=1|page=22|doi=10.7202/045402ar|issn=0701-1008|via=}}</ref> This means that a successful adaptation to changing climatic conditions is attributed to a specific ontology which includes the ability to relate to one's world, making sense of it and reflecting on expectations about it; anticipation. In Greenlandic the term 'anticipation' is divided into two meanings which are primarily used by subsistence hunters and fishermen: ''neriguaa'' (\"to hope for, or to be hopeful of something\") and ''aarleraa'' (\"to be fearful, especially of bad weather\"). This distinction of meanings carries the acceptance of uncertainty as well as potential disappointments and failure.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Geography of Greenland]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.natur.gl/en/ Institute for Natural Resources]\n* [https://gcrc.gl/ Climate Research Centre]\n* [https://www.amap.no/ Arctic Monitoring and Assessment Programme]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Climate of Greenland]]\n[[Category:Effects of global warming|Greenland]]\n[[Category:Climate change and society|Adaptation in Greenland]]\n[[Category:Environment of the Arctic|G]]\n[[Category:Sea ice|Arctic Sea, Global warming]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Flag of Greenland.png|thumb|Flag of Greenland]]\n'''Climate change adaptation''' is a pressing issue '''i'''n [[Greenland]]. The term [[climate change]] describes long-term changes to the [[climate]] system. Since the 1950s a stark rise in global temperatures has been observed.<ref name=\":4\">IPCC (2014): Climate Change 2014: Synthesis Report. Contribution of Working Groups I, II and III to the Fifth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change [Core Writing Team, R.K. Pachauri and L.A. Meyer (eds.)]. IPCC, Geneva, Switzerland, 151 pp.</ref> As climate change, whether [[Climate change (general concept)|natural]] or [[Global warming|anthropogenic]], impacts the livelihoods of people across the globe, responses i.e. ways to prepare and adjust under changing vulnerabilities become important. Such responses are commonly discussed under the term adaptation, \"the process of adjustment to actual or expected climate and its effects\",<ref>IPCC, 2014: Annex II: Glossary [Mach, K.J., S. Planton and C. von Stechow (eds.)]. In: Climate Change 2014: Synthesis Report. Contribution of Working Groups I, II and III to the Fifth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change. IPCC, Geneva, Switzerland, pp. 117-130</ref> as defined by the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change|IPCC]].\n\nGeographically [[Greenland]] is situated between the [[Arctic Ocean|Arctic]] and the [[Atlantic Ocean]], with one third of the island being north of the [[Arctic Circle]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Greenland|title=Greenland {{!}} History, Geography, & Culture|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2018-07-12|language=en}}</ref> Since the middle of the 20th century, the [[Arctic]] has been warming at about twice the global rate.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":7\">Lackenbauer, W., Nicol, H. & Greaves, W. (eds.) (2017). One Arctic. The Arctic Council and Circumpolar Governance. Centre for Foreign Policy & Federation.</ref> Rising temperatures put increasing pressure on certain plant and tree species<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nature.org/ourinitiatives/urgentissues/global-warming-climate-change/threats-solutions/|title=The Threats of Climate Change and Global Warming|website=www.nature.org|language=en|access-date=2018-07-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728131557/https://www.nature.org/ourinitiatives/urgentissues/global-warming-climate-change/threats-solutions/|archive-date=2018-07-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> and contribute to Greenland's melting ice sheet.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/05/climate/greenland-ice-melting.html|title=As Greenland Melts, Where's the Water Going?|last=Fountain|first=Henry|access-date=2018-07-12|language=en}}</ref> This affects and changes the livelihood of the Greenlandic population, particularly the [[Inuit]] people, which make up to 80 percent of the total population.<ref name=\":2\" /> Besides the decline of fish stocks, the country's landscape is changing: the melting ice reveals minerals, oil and gas. This has attracted interest from local and foreign investors for potential resource extraction. As new industries are accompanied by new job opportunities and potential wealth, lifestyles are changing. Greenland is in transition, in terms of biophysical as well as cultural and social conditions.\n\n==Changes and developments ==\n===Biophysical===\n[[File:Greenland ice-sheet hg.jpg|alt=|thumb|Greenland Ice Sheet]]\nDue to its geographical location and global climatic patterns such as the [[North Atlantic oscillation|North Atlantic Oscillation]] and volcanic activity,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Box|first=Jason E.|last2=Yang|first2=Lei|last3=Bromwich|first3=David H.|last4=Bai|first4=Le-Sheng|date=2009|title=Greenland Ice Sheet Surface Air Temperature Variability: 1840\u20132007*|journal=Journal of Climate|language=en|volume=22|issue=14|pages=4029\u20134049|doi=10.1175/2009jcli2816.1|issn=0894-8755|citeseerx=10.1.1.175.1565}}</ref> Greenland is exposed to high levels of fluctuations in the natural environment.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Hamilton|first=Lawrence|last2=Lyster|first2=Per|last3=Otterstad|first3=Oddmund|date=2000|title=Social Change, Ecology and Climate in 20th-Century Greenland|journal=Climatic Change|language=en|volume=47|issue=1/2|pages=193\u2013211|doi=10.1023/a:1005607426021|issn=0165-0009}}</ref> The [[Greenland ice sheet]] is the second largest in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.uga.edu/study-2015-melting-greenland-ice-faster-arctic-warming-0616/|title=Study links 2015 melting Greenland ice to faster Arctic warming - UGA Today|date=2016-06-09|work=UGA Today|access-date=2018-07-12|language=en-US}}</ref> Consequently, its melting has a significant impact on a global scale. According to the [[European Environment Agency|European Environmental Agency]] \"the cumulative ice loss from Greenland from 1992 to 2015 was 3 600 Gt (Gigatonnes) and contributed to global [[sea level rise]] by approximately 10 mm.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eea.europa.eu/data-and-maps/indicators/greenland-ice-sheet-3/assessment|title=Greenland and Antarctic ice sheets|work=European Environment Agency|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en}}</ref> The anticipated warming of the oceans and resulting sea level rise<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipcc.ch/report/ar5/syr/|title=Fifth Assessment Report - Synthesis Report|website=www.ipcc.ch|access-date=2018-07-01}}</ref> result in [[coastal erosion]], melting of [[permafrost]] and decreased [[sea ice]] thickness.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ford|first=James D.|last2=Goldhar|first2=Christina|date=2012-09-25|title=Climate change vulnerability and adaptation in resource dependent communities: a case study from West Greenland|url=https://www.int-res.com/abstracts/cr/v54/n2/p181-196/|journal=Climate Research|language=en|volume=54|issue=2|pages=181\u2013196|doi=10.3354/cr01118|issn=0936-577X}}</ref> The areas impacted most in Greenland are those with the highest population density.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Westergaard-Nielsen|first=Andreas|last2=Karami|first2=Mojtaba|last3=Hansen|first3=Birger Ulf|last4=Westermann|first4=Sebastian|last5=Elberling|first5=Bo|date=2018-01-25|title=Contrasting temperature trends across the ice-free part of Greenland|journal=Scientific Reports|language=En|volume=8|issue=1|pages=1586|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-19992-w|issn=2045-2322|pmc=5785469|pmid=29371633}}</ref>\n\n===Socio-economic===\n[[File:Greenland-CIA WFB Map.png|thumb|Map of Greenland]]\nIn July 2017, Greenland's population was 57,713.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/gl.html|title=The World Factbook \u2014 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-07-12}}</ref> This number is expected to decline to 54,800 by 2030.<ref name=\":9\" /> Historically, the movement of people and the accompanying change of social conditions is nothing unusual for Greenlanders.<ref name=\":8\" /> Recorded shifts were primarily driven by the search for resources (of e.g. seals and cod). At the beginning of the 21st century, climate change has an unprecedented impact on Greenland.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sellheim|first=Nikolas|date=2016|title=Rethinking Greenland and the Arctic in the era of climate change. New northern horizons. Frank Sejersen. 2015. London & New York: Routledge. xii + 235 p, hardcover. ISBN 978-1-13-884515-2. 90.00\u00a3.|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/polar-record/article/rethinking-greenland-and-the-arctic-in-the-era-of-climate-change-new-northern-horizons-frank-sejersen-2015-london-new-york-routledge-xii-235-p-hardcover-isbn-9781138845152-9000/1037251B5398A51B811651E8DED44F6A|journal=Polar Record|language=en|volume=52|issue=4|pages=500\u2013501|doi=10.1017/S0032247415000893|issn=0032-2474|via=}}</ref> The melting ice sheet enables an easier access to oil, gas and minerals, the exploitation of which creates new economic opportunities.<ref name=\":1\">The Government of Greenland: Greenland's oil and Mineral strategy 2014-2018, available under http://naalakkersuisut.gl/~/media/Nanoq/Files/Publications/Raastof/ENG/Greenland%20oil%20and%20mineral%20strategy%202014-2018_ENG.pdf</ref> This prospect of new jobs, purchasing power, new shipping routes and the possibly resulting entrance into the global market system is linked to the potential of gaining greater independence from [[Denmark]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Putting a damper on previously displayed optimism, the versatility of global commodity markets also poses potential threats.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nBesides potential for tourism development which comes with numerous challenges, in south Greenland the melting ice provides more grazing opportunities for farmers. However, there is also apprehension particularly amongst smaller villages that rely on hunting and fishing (primarily Inuit communities), that climate change will contribute to the end of their traditional lifestyles.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Nuttall|first=Mark|date=2010|title=Anticipation, climate change, and movement in Greenland|url=http://id.erudit.org/iderudit/045402ar|journal=\u00c9tudes/Inuit/Studies|language=en|volume=34|issue=1|pages=21|doi=10.7202/045402ar|issn=0701-1008|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Political===\nAlthough becoming increasingly autonomous, Greenland remains dependent on the [[Denmark|Kingdom of Denmark]] since its colonisation in 1721. In 197], the [[Naalakkersuisut|Home Rule Government]] was established in Greenland. It gained further rights in 2009, which moved Greenland towards self-rule.<ref name=\":2\" /> The government is financially dependent on Denmark which provides 60% of Greenland's annual budget revenue.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Nuttall|first=Mark|date=2008|title=Self Rule in Greenland: Towards the World's First Inuit State?|url=|journal=Indigenous Affairs 3-4/08|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> One of the country's greatest challenges is to ensure modern life styles introduced primarily through the industrialisation processes and triggered by intensive fishery while pursuing economic wealth creation and further independence.<ref name=\":9\">AMAP, 2017. Adaptation Actions for a Changing Arctic (AACA) - Baffin Bay / Davis Strait Region Overview report. Arctic Monitoring and Assessment Programme (AMAP), Oslo, Norway. p. 6</ref> It is for this reason or rather the desire to phase out Denmark's financial support entirely that the Home Rule Government strongly supports and even promotes arising opportunities in the extraction industry.<ref name=\":1\" /> The [[United States Geological Survey]] estimated a total of 141 billion barrels of [[hydrocarbon]]s (approximately 13% of the world's undiscovered oil and 30% of the undiscovered natural gas) to be held beneath Greenlandic surfaces.<ref>'''Gautier, Donald L., 2007:''' ''Assessment of undiscovered oil and gas re- sources of the East Greenland Rift Basins Province'' U.S. Geological Survey Fact Sheet 2007-3077, 4 p.</ref> In 2009, the Greenlandic Government published a lifecycle assessment for the production of aluminium in an [[Alcoa]] smelter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smv.gl/Baggrundsrapporter/lca_2009.pdf|title=Life cycle assessment of aluminium production in a new Alcoa smelter in Greenland|last=Schmidt|first=Jannick H|last2=Thrane|first2=Mikkel|date=2009|access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> The construction of the [[Aluminium smelting|aluminium smelter]] is planned in the town of [[Maniitsoq]].<ref name=\":2\" /> In addition, in 2013 the government decided to lift the ban on the extraction of radioactive minerals such as [[uranium]].<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n== Adaptation approaches ==\n\n=== Perspectives on adaptation ===\nIn order to identify and implement effective measures of adaptation, current developments, such as demographic change and other non-climatic factors of change must be considered simultaneously. A study conducted by the Arctic Monitoring and Assessment Programme (AMAP), a working group of the [[Arctic Council]], distinguishes between short-term and long-term adaptation measures, as well as climate-centered and vulnerability-centered options. In the short-term, adaptation measures can focus on immediate challenges caused by increased extreme weather events, such as heavy rainfalls or melting permafrost (climate-centered). In the long-term, other developments, such as the effects of demographic, social and economic change must be considered when determining how climate change will affect the population (vulnerability-centered).<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Adaptation measures ===\n\n==== The Greenlandic Government ====\nAt the [[2015 United Nations Climate Change Conference]], the then Greenlandic Minister for Finance, Mineral Resources and Foreign Affairs, Vittus Qujaukitsoq described climate change adaptation in Greenland as being a policy priority. He underlined the importance of incorporating the knowledge and experience of the Inuit people to gain an all-encompassing understanding of the ongoing climatic changes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://naalakkersuisut.gl/~/media/Nanoq/Files/Attached%20Files/Engelske-tekster/Taler/Climate%20change%20in%20GreenlandParis.pdf|title=Speech by Minister for Finance, Mineral Resources and Foreign Affairs Mr. Vittus Qujaukitsoq}}</ref>\n\nThe government's website ''[http://climategreenland.gl/en/ Climate Greenland]''<ref>'[http://climategreenland.gl/en/ Climate Greenland]'</ref> is both a resource tool to find relevant organizations or stakeholders, as was well as information on the impacts of climate change on Greenland and how the country is responding to it. It focuses on the four areas 'citizen', 'trade', 'municipality' and 'education'. Climate Change Adaptation is defined as \"being prepared for the challenges caused by the climate changes and about relating to possibilities as well as challenges.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://climategreenland.gl/en/citizen/climate-adaptation/|title=Climate adaptation - Climate Greenland|work=Climate Greenland|access-date=2018-07-04|language=en-US}}</ref> The Government publishes adaptation reports for sectors, such as fisheries, hunting or [[Tourism in Greenland|tourism]].\n\nIn 2009 the Greenland Climate Research Centre was set up in the capital of Greenland, [[Nuuk]]. The centre received a grant of [[Danish krone|DKK]] 35 million by the [[Ministry of Higher Education and Science (Denmark)|Danish Ministry of Science, Technology and Innovation]]. The aim of the centre is to study the impact of climate change on Greenland [[Climate change in the Arctic|and the Arctic]] and the consequences for nature and society. It is linked to the Greenland Institute of Natural Resources and the [[University of Greenland]], Ilisimatusarfik.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.natur.gl/en/communication/news/article/a/new-greenland-climate-research-center/|title=New Greenland Climate Research Center {{!}} Pinngortitaleriffik - Gr\u00f8nlands Naturinstitut|website=www.natur.gl|language=da|access-date=2018-07-04}}</ref>\n\n==== The Arctic Council ====\n[[File:Arctic region CIA.jpg|alt=|thumb|Countries within the Arctic Region]]\nIn 2008, following increased media attention for the Arctic, the five countries adjacent to the [[Arctic Ocean]] (Canada, Denmark (Greenland), Norway, Russia and the United States) published the [[Ilulissat Declaration]]. This proclaims the Arctic states' responsibility to protect the ecosystem of the Arctic Ocean.<ref name=\":7\" /> In addition, the [[Arctic Council|Council's]] Arctic Monitoring and Assessment Programme (AMAP) has published a series of reports one of which looks at adaptation in particular. The 2017 Adaptation Actions for a Changing Arctic (AACA) Report covers the [[Baffin Bay]]/[[Davis Strait]] region which includes the western part of Greenland aiming to offer information \"to assist local decision makers and stakeholders [...] in developing adaptation tools and strategies to better deal with climate change [...].\"<ref name=\":9\" /> Following extensive stakeholder dialogues, the report identified seven themes of local adaptation:\n\n# Living resources\n# Non-living resources (e.g. mineral extraction)\n# Education\n# Human health and well-being\n# Tourism\n# Shipping\n# Infrastructure\n\nThe report concludes that it is crucial to consider the cumulative and cascading effects of change in order to build adaptive capacities. Suggested measures are structural/physical, social as well as institutional. Lastly, as a precursor to adaptation measures, the AACA points out six factors (political leadership, institutional organisation, local and regional leadership, the need for usable science and sufficient funding and public support) to build adaptive readiness.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n== Inuit culture and tradition ==\n=== Traditional ecological knowledge ===\nWidely discussed in academic literature since the 1980s, [[traditional ecological knowledge]] cumulatively consists of knowledge, practices and beliefs about the interaction of living beings and their environment.<ref>Berkes, F. (2008). ''Sacred Ecology.'' New York: Routledge.</ref> In Greenland, traditional knowledge does not only underpin the life of subsistence hunters and fishermen but also more broadly community life and [[Inuit culture|culture]]. While climate change is making practical aspects such as the prediction of weather or animal migration more difficult, it also highlights the importance of traditional knowledge for adaptive capacity building in other areas e.g. the recognition of approaching hazards and survival skills.<ref name=\":9\" /> The process of knowledge transfer between generations for building resilience is also important to address as it is weakened by trends of urbanisation and alternative livelihoods. Such trends can further lead to the alienation of people from their environment. This increases the need for the management of ecosystems which are the base of [[Economy of Greenland|Greenland's]] economic activities, cultural characteristics and natural services.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== The concept of anticipation ===\n[[File:Leaving Kulusuk (33806528314).jpg|thumb|Inuit hunters near Kulusuk, Greenland]]\n[[Greenlandic Inuit]] as a societal group are academically recognised for their \"finely tuned ability to be flexible, to innovate, and to seize opportunities in the environment.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nuttall|first=Mark|date=2010|title=Anticipation, climate change, and movement in Greenland|url=http://www.erudit.org/fr/revues/etudinuit/2010-v34-n1-etudinuit3992/045402ar/|journal=&#201;tudes/Inuit/Studies|language=en|volume=34|issue=1|page=22|doi=10.7202/045402ar|issn=0701-1008|via=}}</ref> This means that a successful adaptation to changing climatic conditions is attributed to a specific ontology which includes the ability to relate to one's world, making sense of it and reflecting on expectations about it; anticipation. In Greenlandic the term 'anticipation' is divided into two meanings which are primarily used by subsistence hunters and fishermen: ''neriguaa'' (\"to hope for, or to be hopeful of something\") and ''aarleraa'' (\"to be fearful, especially of bad weather\"). This distinction of meanings carries the acceptance of uncertainty as well as potential disappointments and failure.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Geography of Greenland]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.natur.gl/en/ Institute for Natural Resources]\n* [https://gcrc.gl/ Climate Research Centre]\n* [https://www.amap.no/ Arctic Monitoring and Assessment Programme]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Climate of Greenland]]\n[[Category:Effects of global warming|Greenland]]\n[[Category:Climate change and society|Adaptation in Greenland]]\n[[Category:Environment of the Arctic|G]]\n[[Category:Sea ice|Arctic Sea, Global warming]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8003:a601:e800:c127:35d4:9a40:5b6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(added stuff they forgot)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_change_adaptation_in_Greenland"}
